YAML vs JSON
  - We can write open api defination in 2 format yaml and json, structure of both is almost same, but diffrence lies in the format followed to represent the structure of document
   - yaml involves fewer keystroke and easier to type and read, in case of yaml no need quotes to define the strings 

How to build an OpenAPI Specification using YAML?
     Open api specification is a format that is being used to develop an api in a standardized format, so whenever you want to design an api and share it across your teams or other third party teams, we strongly recommend you to create this open api specification document. The advantage of using open api is that since it is a standardized format for defining the apis, all the stakeholders will able to understand it a simpler way.
    Consider we have college management system wherein we are going to create a simple api that is going to get the list of all courses available in the system
    To create the open api specification we use one of the popular editor namely swagger editor,
to access it we use https://editor.swagger.io/, where we can see sample open api specification that has been given by this tool.
   Let's get started with creating the open api specification for cms using yaml

1. Let's include a comment, so to create a doc comment you use hash in the case of yaml

#CMS OpenAPI

2. Now we create simple key value pair, we use one of the key called openapi that refers to the version of the open api called 3.0.3

openapi: 3.0.3

You can ignore errors that is appearing at the right side, because open api specification requires
certain mandatory parameters, it is going to validate continuously for the input that has been given and give us the corresponding warnings and the errors, by the end all these errors will be resolved 

3. Next we create a mapping, we create a new entry called "info" which is a key and this is going to contain multiple key value pairs
   info is considered as a complex type, since it contains one or more key value pairs, it contains the title with a value as open api specification for cms and the second one being the version followed by 1.2 (to specify any string value in yaml we have to use ' ' or " " or !!str)

info:
  title: OpenAPI Specification for CMS
  version: '1.2'

4. Next we add a similar key value pair called "externalDocs" that refers to the documentation that is used for the third party people, this comes again with a set of key value pairs called "description" which gives more information about cms api, and it again contains with "url" which
include a url for this documentation

externalDocs:
   description: More information about CMS API
   url: http://mycollege.com/api

5. The open api specification supports another field called "servers" used to define a list of servers available for your api. When you have your web api service, you can host them in multiple services, so open api uses the servers section to
define the url where your web service is running. Since open api supports more than one service to be defined, in the case of yaml it is considered as a collection type and to represent a collection in yaml we use dash followed by the list of values.

- It shows that our current web service is hosted under url, since it support more than one url, we need to enter the second one as url followed by another url value.

servers:
   - url: http://localhost:44333/api 
   - url: http://localhost:{port}/stagingapi             
 
But we want to make the port as configurable, open api supports a concept called "variables" to define or declare the variable called port,  again as per the open api specification it uses a key called variables to define the list of all variables used within this url.

     variables:
        port:
          enum:
            - "44333"
            - '8990'
          default: !!str 44333

    This is going to contain an "enum" to define the list of all port numbers in string,  and then it provides one more property called "default" among these two port numbers which want to be considered as the default value, this is considered as int by default to make it as a string we can use single quote or double quote or you can use secondary name space that is represented using
double exclamation marks,  once you use the double exclamation followed by a specific type namely
string in this case whatever the value is going to come here is going to consider as a
string 

servers:
   - url: http://localhost:44333/api
   - url: http://localhost:{port}/stagingapi
     variables:
        port:
          enum:
            - "44333"
            - '8990'
          default: !!str 44333


6. Next we define "tags" an another collection type which can use to group the list of apis under a specific name

tags:
  - name: course
    description: Operation about Courses


So when we continuously develop the cms api in the left hand side, in the right side you can see the representation of the api in the ui format on swagger ui 

7. The final and the most important part with respect to the open api specification is defining the actual paths, these paths refers to the actual resources on the list of api endpoints within that resource
   So for our current api we are going to define a resource as courses with one api endpoint namely getCourses which is going to get all the courses from the system 

- We are going to use the key called "paths" define the actual resource namely /courses in our
case, this is followed by defining a list of key value pairs to define the endpoints for this courses. So we use a tag called "summary" to give a summary for this specific endpoint

paths:
  /courses:
      summary: Operation about course

- Next we define the list of all verbs provided by the http, since we want to get all the courses so we use http "get" and tag it with one or more values that we have defined before called course, again we can give a summary for this specific verb called get all the courses

paths:
  /courses:
      summary: Operation about course
         get:
           tags:
              - course
           summary: Get all the courses

- Next we define the responses for this api using "responses" and we provide different responses like 200, 400 etc and for each response we give some description

paths:
  /courses:
      summary: Operation about course
      get:
        tags:
          - course
        summary: Get all the courses
        responses:
           200:
             description: Success
           400:
             description: Incorrect input
           default:
             description: Success

On the right hand side we can notice that we have a single get request /courses which gets all the courses and we have the list of responses been defined with code description and corresponding links


